+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: 758 consultants run through 18 realistic business tasks | Source: VERIFIED (Dell'Acqua, Edelman, McFowland, Mollick, Mollick, Lifshitz-Assaf, Kellogg, Krayer, Rajendran, Lakhani, \"Navigating the Jagged Frontier: Field Experimental Evidence of the Effects of AI on Knowledge Worker Productivity and Quality,\" Harvard Business School Working Paper 24-013, September 2023 — methodology section, sample size and task design)\nClaim: Half had GPT-4 access | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — randomized control trial design)\nClaim: 12% more tasks completed, 25% faster, 40% higher quality (inside frontier) | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — headline findings; precise figures 12.2%, 25.1%, ~40%)\nClaim: Outside the frontier, AI users did worse than the control group | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — \"jagged frontier\" finding; AI users were 19 percentage points more likely to provide incorrect answers on out-of-frontier tasks)\nClaim: Centaur and Cyborg working patterns labeled in the paper | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — qualitative analysis section identifies these two usage patterns)\nClaim: Pilot Week 5 is Iterate & Inherit (give the build to a teammate, watch where it breaks) | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html — Week 5 section: \"Take what you built, give it to a teammate, watch where it breaks, fix it\")\nClaim: Week 4 was \"build something worth keeping\" | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html — Week 4 section: \"Build Worth Keeping\")\nClaim: Week 5 challenge involves teammate handoff and capstone scoping | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html — Week 5 Challenge: \"Take the teammate's feedback from Week 4. Cut what's thin, sharpen what's vague\")\nEditorial: Framing the Dell'Acqua finding as a Week 5 inheritance test is Preston's pedagogical synthesis applied to the pilot's iteration focus, not a frame the original authors use.\nEditorial: \"The first version is a guess about where the frontier sits. The second version, written after a teammate hits the edge, is the one that knows\" is Preston's framing of the iteration-as-frontier-discovery insight implicit in the Cyborg pattern.\nEditorial: Resource URL is the SSRN abstract page for HBS WP 24-013; if the link resolves stale, the canonical citation (HBS WP 24-013, September 2023) remains accurate and discoverable by title search.\nAdversarial review 20260504 (rev 1): Em-dash count: 0 (well under the 2-per-piece limit). Forbidden phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical use; \"Navigating\" appears only in source paper title in sourceNotes), landscape, ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, pivotal, spearhead, showcase, underscore, doing the heavy lifting, the real question is, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting. Contrastive \"X, not Y\" or \"not X but Y\" constructions: zero. Rhetorical questions in body: zero. Opens with concrete fact (758 consultants, 18 tasks, 12%/25%/40%). \"However/Moreover/Furthermore/Additionally\": zero. Word count main body: 257 (inside 240–280 band). Try This: 59 (inside 40–80 band). Try This precisely mirrors the Week 5 Iterate & Scope challenge (teammate handoff, two-column observation) so the briefing and the live curriculum reinforce the same action.",
